The paper proposes a modeling approach for IoT analytics based on learning embodied agents, which involves a variability model of IoT embodied agents, feedback evaluative machine learning, and reconfiguration of a group of agents in accordance with environmental context. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) and Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-categories. Additionally, the paper addresses the challenges of deploying IoT applications in specific settings, which involves the complex static and dynamic variability of physical devices, software application behavior, and the environment. This suggests that the paper may also belong to the Software Engineering (cs.SE), Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC), and Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-categories.
